	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Beyond commodity-driven growth and SADC regional integration </h1>

			
			<h4>
												23 April 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Speaking at the sixth Africa Economic Forum in March 2012, South Africa’s Minister of Trade and Industry, Rob Davies, has warned of the need ‘to turn ... commodities-driven growth into a serious effort to create value-added products’. Africa is currently a major market for South Africa’s value-added product exports, with South Africa running a trade surplus on its Africa trade, while carrying a trade deficit on its trade with developed country partners. A key strategy is to promote agro-processing activities.</p><p>Fully implementing the SADC FTA and extending it to the trilateral FTA area are seen as important tools for promoting intra-African trade and, by implication, growth in value-added product trade. Trade Minister Davies expressed the view that priority should first be given to ‘consolidating’ SADC, ‘before continuing with deeper integration on the continent’.</p><p>However, a SADC Secretariat review of the Regional Indicative Strategic Development Plan (RISDP) has argued that some of the established targets for regional integration are ‘unrealistic and need revision’, and that ‘overall implementation of the RISDP is fraught with challenges’. Particular challenges include ‘domesticating’ regional policy commitments – making them appropriate to the national contexts – and lack of follow-up to ministerial decisions, as well as lack of consultation among key stakeholders.</p><p>SADC’s plans for a customs union, initially scheduled for 2010, have now been ‘postponed indefinitely’, and the targets of establishing a ‘common market, monetary union and economic union with a single currency in 2015, 2016 and 2018 respectively, are now in doubt’. It is claimed that ‘from 2001, phased tariff elimination has remained problematic’, while ‘elimination of non-tariff barriers to trade, a process that started in 2007, is still ongoing.’ It was noted that ‘Malawi is struggling with a tariff phase down since 2004, while Zimbabwe requested derogation to suspend tariff phase downs from 2010 until 2012.’ In addition, ‘In 2011, Tanzania applied for derogation to levy 25 percent import duty on sugar and paper products until 2015.’</p><p>Despite these issues, intra-regional trade grew between 2000 and 2009 from 15.7% of total external trade to 18.5%. According to the SADC Secretariat, ‘The existence of multiple memberships (of regional economic groups) by SADC member states has complicated the efforts of attaining the customs union as planned.’ The ‘lack of implementation of agreed harmonised regional policies’, is also seen as ‘a big hurdle to integration’.</p><p>In terms of non-tariff barriers to trade, South Africa’s Deputy President has identified three main areas that need to be addressed: improving operations at border posts to reduce delays; improving poor infrastructure; and promoting industrial diversification. Trade and Industry Minister Rob Davies accorded highest priority to getting to grips with regional infrastructure constraints and the production of more appropriate goods and services, and addressing regulatory and non-tariff policy measures were seen as secondary. Dr Davies maintained that ‘If we can’t produce goods that are going to sell in each other’s markets we aren’t going to get the benefits of each other’s markets.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Engineering News Online</i> (Johannesburg), ‘Davies says intra-African trade is key to SA growth’, 8 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/08/davies-says-intra-african-trade-is-key-to-sa-growth/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/08/davies-says-intra-african-trade-is-key-...</a></p><p><i>The Southern Times </i>(Windhoek), ‘SADC integration: Reality check’, 19 March 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/19/sadc-integration-reality-check/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/19/sadc-integration-reality-check/</a></p><p><i>The Citizen</i> (Cape Town), ‘Regional trade key to SA growth’, 5 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/05/regional-trade-key-to-sa-growth/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/05/regional-trade-key-to-sa-growth/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Given the difficulties faced in following through on regional tariff elimination commitments and commitments to the removal of policy-driven non-tariff barriers to trade within the SADC context, the focus appears to be shifting firmly towards infrastructure development and the facilitation of cross-border trade by improving the functioning of border posts. The assumption seems to be that if real material gains can be achieved by making improvement in these areas, then foundations will be laid for getting to grips with the more contention areas of tariff dismantling and more transparent regulation (rather than removal) of the use of non-tariff policy measures.</p><p>An approach involving more transparent regulation of the use of non-tariff measures would accommodate the existing practices within overlapping regional integration initiatives (i.e. SACU/SADC and the EAC/COMESA). This is particularly relevant in the agricultural sector where these policy measures are most commonly used. Building from the grassroots upwards may well prove more effective now that the broad vision for future trade relations is in place. However, establishing clear national policy frameworks (e.g. for agro-industrial development), which are then progressively harmonised, would also appear essential. At present, only two SADC members (South Africa and Mauritius) have such policies in place. While others are under development (e.g. in Namibia), this may involve the use of non-tariff trade policy tools to support attainment of national sector development objectives. </p>
		</div>
		
